    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="poem">
                <pb facs="MSVIIIp3-4r"/>
                <fw type="pageNum" place="top-right">4</fw>
                <lg type="stanza">
                    <l>A poet is a very foolish stay</l>
                    <l>I mustnt call em idiotical</l>
                    <l>I cant abuse em<unclear resp="#SB">.</unclear> Yet I think I may</l>
                    <l>Although it is a very ticklish topic all</l>
                    <l>Must here allow me<unclear resp="#SB">.</unclear> But I here will say</l>
                    <l>Evn though I be thought misanthropical</l>
                    <l>That of each racked nay more unlaurelled fate</l>
                    <l>The worst of alls a poet Laureate</l>
                </lg>
                <lg type="stanza">
                    <l>Oh thou Poor Southey<note n="n" type="gloss" resp="#DCH">In his <date when="1830">1830</date> diary, <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName> had written respectfully of <persName corresp="#RS">Southey</persName>, after the family had ogled him in church, during their tour of the <placeName corresp="#LAKES">Lakes</placeName> (<hi rend="underline">TLC</hi> 42)<!--Need info here.-->; and by <date when="1831-03">March 1831</date> in &#x201C;Iteriad,&#x201D; he had drafted the lines on the poet&#x02BC;s &#x201C;dark lightning eye&#x201D; that &#x201C;made him seem half inspired / Or like a New Thalaba<!--Need info here.--> vengefully fired,&#x201D; referring to <persName corresp="#RS">Southey</persName>&#x02BC;s <hi rend="underline">Thalaba the Destroyer</hi> (2:299&#x2013;300; MS VI, 72).</note> But tis now too late</l>
                    <l>Thou knowest not thy woeful situation</l>
                    <l>Oh how I pity thy most wretched fate</l>
                    <l>But nothing now remains save lamentation</l>
                    <l>Thou art <del rend="strikethrough"><unclear resp="#SB">unstabled</unclear></del><add place="above"><space quantity="10" unit="chars"/>appointed</add> poet laureate</l>
                    <l>In this rotunda orbe the worst station</l>
                    <l>Alas thy brow of bays will now be bold</l>
                    <l>Because because because thou wert installed</l>
                </lg>
                <lg type="stanza">
                    <l>On every birthday of reforming Bill</l>
                    <l>As regularly they come round again</l>
                    <l>And (I should hope it was against your<add place="above"><space quantity="31" unit="chars"/><g type="addon">-</g>will</add></l>
                    <l>For birthday images must rack your brain</l>
                    <l>And lines most complimentary instil</l>
                    <l>That always signify the very same</l>
                    <l>When not a goose then much less a goose quill</l>
                    <l>Will run on rapidly against its will<note n="n" type="gloss" resp="#DCH">2As an ultra-Tory, Southey was opposed to the Reform Bill. Ruskin apparently is not referring to a recent publication by Southey. Although in <date notBefore="1831-06-21" notAfter="1831-09-22">summer 1831</date> the poet drafted colloquies on political topics, he abandoned the project when the Reform Bill proved inevitable (Geoffrey Carnall, Robert Southey and His Age: The Development of a Conservative Mind [Oxford: Clarendon, 1960], 185-88).</note></l>
                </lg>
            </div>            
